<paragraph blockId="17.[189,334,1287,1313]" box="[189,334,1287,1313]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,334,1287,1313]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,334,1287,1313]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Description</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[188,1400,1334,1677]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
BODY. Shape oval. Length 
<quantity box="[499,582,1334,1360]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.3" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" unit="cm" value="2.3">2.3 cm</quantity>
. Smooth dorsal surface. Background color dark to velvety brown with white dots and spots that draw a longitudinal line along the body axis. One thin bright yellow external line and another internal and black line surround the entire body margin. The yellow one is interrupted at the pseudotentacles level (
<figureCitation box="[529,598,1439,1465]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="16.[189,232,1748,1774]" captionTargetBox="[195,1395,886,1702]" captionTargetId="figure-208@16.[189,1399,883,1718]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="Fig. 3. A–D. Prostheceraeus crisostomum sp. nov. (MNCN 4.01/2684 to 2698). A. Whole live animal, dorsal view. B. Anterior region with cerebral eyes cluster and tentacles (black arrows). C. Histological section of the reproductive system stained with AZAN. D. Histological section of the whole animal stained with AZAN and sagittal reconstruction. – E–I. Pseudoceros rawlinsonae var. galaxy (MNCN 4.01/2729 to 2798). E. Whole live animal, dorsal view. F. Anterior region with eyes cluster and tentacles (white arrows). G. Whole live animal, ventral view. H. Histological sagittal section of male and female copulatory organ. I. Sagittal reconstruction of the reproductive system. Abbreviations: see Material and methods." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4561533" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4561533/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
E–F). Marginal body edges lined with transversal whitish elongated drops (
<figureCitation box="[270,358,1474,1501]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="16.[189,232,1748,1774]" captionTargetBox="[195,1395,886,1702]" captionTargetId="figure-208@16.[189,1399,883,1718]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="Fig. 3. A–D. Prostheceraeus crisostomum sp. nov. (MNCN 4.01/2684 to 2698). A. Whole live animal, dorsal view. B. Anterior region with cerebral eyes cluster and tentacles (black arrows). C. Histological section of the reproductive system stained with AZAN. D. Histological section of the whole animal stained with AZAN and sagittal reconstruction. – E–I. Pseudoceros rawlinsonae var. galaxy (MNCN 4.01/2729 to 2798). E. Whole live animal, dorsal view. F. Anterior region with eyes cluster and tentacles (white arrows). G. Whole live animal, ventral view. H. Histological sagittal section of male and female copulatory organ. I. Sagittal reconstruction of the reproductive system. Abbreviations: see Material and methods." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4561533" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4561533/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Fig. 3F</figureCitation>
). Ventral coloration dark grey to black. Ventral sucker in the middle of the body (
<figureCitation box="[1292,1385,1474,1501]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="16.[189,232,1748,1774]" captionTargetBox="[195,1395,886,1702]" captionTargetId="figure-208@16.[189,1399,883,1718]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="Fig. 3. A–D. Prostheceraeus crisostomum sp. nov. (MNCN 4.01/2684 to 2698). A. Whole live animal, dorsal view. B. Anterior region with cerebral eyes cluster and tentacles (black arrows). C. Histological section of the reproductive system stained with AZAN. D. Histological section of the whole animal stained with AZAN and sagittal reconstruction. – E–I. Pseudoceros rawlinsonae var. galaxy (MNCN 4.01/2729 to 2798). E. Whole live animal, dorsal view. F. Anterior region with eyes cluster and tentacles (white arrows). G. Whole live animal, ventral view. H. Histological sagittal section of male and female copulatory organ. I. Sagittal reconstruction of the reproductive system. Abbreviations: see Material and methods." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4561533" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4561533/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Fig. 3G</figureCitation>
). Pseudotentacles constitute two simple folds that present each of them a small cluster of tentacular eyes in their margin. Round cluster of cerebral eyes present and surrounded by a spot of white pigment. Pharynx ruffled, butterfly-shaped and located at the anterior third of the body. Oral pore, female and male gonopore close to each other and located at the anterior end (
<figureCitation box="[990,1086,1615,1641]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="16.[189,232,1748,1774]" captionTargetBox="[195,1395,886,1702]" captionTargetId="figure-208@16.[189,1399,883,1718]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="Fig. 3. A–D. Prostheceraeus crisostomum sp. nov. (MNCN 4.01/2684 to 2698). A. Whole live animal, dorsal view. B. Anterior region with cerebral eyes cluster and tentacles (black arrows). C. Histological section of the reproductive system stained with AZAN. D. Histological section of the whole animal stained with AZAN and sagittal reconstruction. – E–I. Pseudoceros rawlinsonae var. galaxy (MNCN 4.01/2729 to 2798). E. Whole live animal, dorsal view. F. Anterior region with eyes cluster and tentacles (white arrows). G. Whole live animal, ventral view. H. Histological sagittal section of male and female copulatory organ. I. Sagittal reconstruction of the reproductive system. Abbreviations: see Material and methods." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4561533" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4561533/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Fig. 3G</figureCitation>
). Male and female genital pores located after the pharynx in the anterior half of the body (
<figureCitation box="[936,1004,1650,1677]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="16.[189,232,1748,1774]" captionTargetBox="[195,1395,886,1702]" captionTargetId="figure-208@16.[189,1399,883,1718]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="Fig. 3. A–D. Prostheceraeus crisostomum sp. nov. (MNCN 4.01/2684 to 2698). A. Whole live animal, dorsal view. B. Anterior region with cerebral eyes cluster and tentacles (black arrows). C. Histological section of the reproductive system stained with AZAN. D. Histological section of the whole animal stained with AZAN and sagittal reconstruction. – E–I. Pseudoceros rawlinsonae var. galaxy (MNCN 4.01/2729 to 2798). E. Whole live animal, dorsal view. F. Anterior region with eyes cluster and tentacles (white arrows). G. Whole live animal, ventral view. H. Histological sagittal section of male and female copulatory organ. I. Sagittal reconstruction of the reproductive system. Abbreviations: see Material and methods." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4561533" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4561533/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
H–I).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[188,1400,1716,1989]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
MALE REPRODUCTIVE SYSTEM. Male genital pore between the posterior lobes of the ruffled pharynx. Male copulatory organ dorso-ventrally orientated consists in a prostatic vesicle and a very muscular seminal vesicle, as well as a penis papilla armed with a stylet (
<figureCitation box="[831,900,1786,1812]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="16.[189,232,1748,1774]" captionTargetBox="[195,1395,886,1702]" captionTargetId="figure-208@16.[189,1399,883,1718]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="Fig. 3. A–D. Prostheceraeus crisostomum sp. nov. (MNCN 4.01/2684 to 2698). A. Whole live animal, dorsal view. B. Anterior region with cerebral eyes cluster and tentacles (black arrows). C. Histological section of the reproductive system stained with AZAN. D. Histological section of the whole animal stained with AZAN and sagittal reconstruction. – E–I. Pseudoceros rawlinsonae var. galaxy (MNCN 4.01/2729 to 2798). E. Whole live animal, dorsal view. F. Anterior region with eyes cluster and tentacles (white arrows). G. Whole live animal, ventral view. H. Histological sagittal section of male and female copulatory organ. I. Sagittal reconstruction of the reproductive system. Abbreviations: see Material and methods." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4561533" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4561533/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
H–I). 
<emphasis box="[972,1154,1786,1812]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Vasa deferentia</emphasis>
open separately into the seminal vesicle. Seminal vesicle rounded, frontally oriented and lined with a thick muscular wall. Prostatic vesicle rounded, muscular and smaller than the seminal vesicle. Sperm duct muscular and long, extends frontally to join the prostatic duct inside the proximal end of the conical stylet. The short ejaculatory duct appears surrounded by the stylet cone and the penis sheath. The male atrium is wide and tetra-folding (fork-like) as characteristic of the genus (
<figureCitation box="[826,908,1962,1988]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="16.[189,232,1748,1774]" captionTargetBox="[195,1395,886,1702]" captionTargetId="figure-208@16.[189,1399,883,1718]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="Fig. 3. A–D. Prostheceraeus crisostomum sp. nov. (MNCN 4.01/2684 to 2698). A. Whole live animal, dorsal view. B. Anterior region with cerebral eyes cluster and tentacles (black arrows). C. Histological section of the reproductive system stained with AZAN. D. Histological section of the whole animal stained with AZAN and sagittal reconstruction. – E–I. Pseudoceros rawlinsonae var. galaxy (MNCN 4.01/2729 to 2798). E. Whole live animal, dorsal view. F. Anterior region with eyes cluster and tentacles (white arrows). G. Whole live animal, ventral view. H. Histological sagittal section of male and female copulatory organ. I. Sagittal reconstruction of the reproductive system. Abbreviations: see Material and methods." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4561533" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4561533/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Fig. 3I</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[189,1398,265,327]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">FEMALE REPRODUCTIVE SYSTEM. With a short muscular vagina, backwards oriented and surrounded by cement glands.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="18" pageNumber="19" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="18.[189,303,366,392]" box="[189,303,366,392]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,303,366,392]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,303,366,392]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Remarks</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[188,1399,412,720]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
The genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lang" authorityYear="1884" box="[319,468,412,438]" class="Rhabditophora" family="Pseudoceritidae" genus="Pseudoceros" kingdom="Animalia" order="Polycladida" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[319,468,412,438]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Pseudoceros</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
comprises approximately 89 species with similar copulatory organs, but bright and unique coloration patterns. However, within these patterns some taxa share evident similarities. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cuadrado &amp; Rodríguez &amp; Moro &amp; Grande &amp; Noreña" authorityYear="2021" box="[189,622,482,509]" class="Rhabditophora" family="Pseudoceritidae" genus="Pseudoceros" kingdom="Animalia" order="Polycladida" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="variety" species="rawlinsonae" variety="galaxy">
<emphasis box="[189,489,482,508]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Pseudoceros rawlinsonae</emphasis>
var. 
<emphasis box="[544,622,482,508]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">galaxy</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
shares with 
<taxonomicName authority="Verril, 1902" authorityName="Verril" authorityYear="1902" box="[765,1025,482,509]" class="Rhabditophora" family="Pseudoceritidae" genus="Pseudoceros" kingdom="Animalia" order="Polycladida" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="bicolor">
<emphasis box="[765,877,482,508]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">P. bicolor</emphasis>
Verril, 1902
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cuadrado, Moro &amp; Norena" authorityYear="2017" box="[1034,1170,483,508]" class="Rhabditophora" family="Pseudoceritidae" genus="Pseudoceros" kingdom="Animalia" order="Polycladida" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="mororum">
<emphasis box="[1034,1170,483,508]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">P. mororum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Bolanos, Quiroga &amp; Litvaitis, 2007" authorityName="Bolanos, Quiroga &amp; Litvaitis" authorityYear="2007" class="Rhabditophora" family="Pseudoceritidae" genus="Pseudoceros" kingdom="Animalia" order="Polycladida" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="rawlinsonae">
<emphasis box="[1225,1397,482,508]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">P. rawlinsonae</emphasis>
Bolaños, Quiroga &amp; Litvaitis, 2007
</taxonomicName>
the brown background and one whitish, broad marginal band, but in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Verril" authorityYear="1902" box="[219,332,553,579]" class="Rhabditophora" family="Pseudoceritidae" genus="Pseudoceros" kingdom="Animalia" order="Polycladida" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="bicolor">
<emphasis box="[219,332,553,579]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">P. bicolor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the marginal band is wide with inner waves (
<bibRefCitation author="Litvaitis M. &amp; Bolanos D. M. &amp; Quiroga S. Y." box="[860,1094,553,579]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" pagination="829 - 845" refId="ref18242" refString="Litvaitis M. K, Bolanos D. M. &amp; Quiroga S. Y. 2010. When names are wrong and colours deceive: unravelling the Pseudoceros bicolor species complex (Turbellaria: Polycladida). Journal of Natural History 44: 829 - 845. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 00222930903537074" type="journal article" year="2010">
Litvaitis 
<emphasis box="[966,1017,553,579]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">et al</emphasis>
. 2010
</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 4a–i); 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bolanos, Quiroga &amp; Litvaitis" authorityYear="2007" box="[1225,1398,553,579]" class="Rhabditophora" family="Pseudoceritidae" genus="Pseudoceros" kingdom="Animalia" order="Polycladida" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="rawlinsonae">
<emphasis box="[1225,1398,553,579]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">P. rawlinsonae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
shows, in addition to the wide band, a thin orange line (
<bibRefCitation author="Litvaitis M. &amp; Bolanos D. M. &amp; Quiroga S. Y." box="[852,1091,588,614]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" pagination="829 - 845" refId="ref18242" refString="Litvaitis M. K, Bolanos D. M. &amp; Quiroga S. Y. 2010. When names are wrong and colours deceive: unravelling the Pseudoceros bicolor species complex (Turbellaria: Polycladida). Journal of Natural History 44: 829 - 845. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 00222930903537074" type="journal article" year="2010">
Litvaitis 
<emphasis box="[961,1020,588,614]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">et al.</emphasis>
2010
</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 4j–p); in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cuadrado, Moro &amp; Norena" authorityYear="2017" box="[1260,1398,589,614]" class="Rhabditophora" family="Pseudoceritidae" genus="Pseudoceros" kingdom="Animalia" order="Polycladida" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="mororum">
<emphasis box="[1260,1398,589,614]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">P. mororum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the whitish band is interrupted and drop-shaped and additionally, two orange marginal stripes border the entire body (
<bibRefCitation author="Cuadrado C. &amp; Moro L. &amp; Norena C." box="[335,586,658,685]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" pagination="38 - 68" refId="ref16432" refString="Cuadrado C., Moro L. &amp; Norena C. 2017. The Polycladida (Platyhelminthes) of the Canary Islands. New genus, species and records. Zootaxa 4312: 38 - 68. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4312.1.2" type="journal article" year="2017">
Cuadrado 
<emphasis box="[458,509,658,684]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">et al</emphasis>
. 2017
</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 6a–b); finally, the 
<collectingRegion box="[853,913,659,685]" country="South Africa" name="Western Cape" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Cape</collectingRegion>
Verdean species shows, together with the drop-shaped white band, two black and orange thin lines (
<figureCitation box="[869,937,694,720]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="16.[189,232,1748,1774]" captionTargetBox="[195,1395,886,1702]" captionTargetId="figure-208@16.[189,1399,883,1718]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="Fig. 3. A–D. Prostheceraeus crisostomum sp. nov. (MNCN 4.01/2684 to 2698). A. Whole live animal, dorsal view. B. Anterior region with cerebral eyes cluster and tentacles (black arrows). C. Histological section of the reproductive system stained with AZAN. D. Histological section of the whole animal stained with AZAN and sagittal reconstruction. – E–I. Pseudoceros rawlinsonae var. galaxy (MNCN 4.01/2729 to 2798). E. Whole live animal, dorsal view. F. Anterior region with eyes cluster and tentacles (white arrows). G. Whole live animal, ventral view. H. Histological sagittal section of male and female copulatory organ. I. Sagittal reconstruction of the reproductive system. Abbreviations: see Material and methods." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4561533" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4561533/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
E–F).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[188,1399,759,962]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
Although the four previously mentioned species can be clearly differentiated due to their coloration, this is not the case in the molecular analysis (Fig. 8). In both the Bayesian and Maximum Likelihood analyses, individuals from 
<collectingCountry box="[515,653,829,856]" name="Cape Verde" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Cape Verde</collectingCountry>
appear closely related to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bolanos, Quiroga &amp; Litvaitis" authorityYear="2007" box="[966,1143,829,855]" class="Rhabditophora" family="Pseudoceritidae" genus="Pseudoceros" kingdom="Animalia" order="Polycladida" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="rawlinsonae">
<emphasis box="[966,1143,829,855]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">P. rawlinsonae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, so much so that the separation of both populations (the Cape Verdean population and the Caribbean population) is only possible at the level of variety, not of species. Therefore, we determined the individuals from 
<collectingCountry box="[1264,1398,900,926]" name="Cape Verde" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Cape Verde</collectingCountry>
as a 
<taxonomicName box="[240,403,935,961]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" rank="variety" variety="within">variety within</taxonomicName>
the species 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bolanos, Quiroga &amp; Litvaitis" authorityYear="2007" box="[547,721,935,961]" class="Rhabditophora" family="Pseudoceritidae" genus="Pseudoceros" kingdom="Animalia" order="Polycladida" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="rawlinsonae">
<emphasis box="[547,721,935,961]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">P. rawlinsonae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[189,1401,1001,1133]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
Nonetheless, we want to emphasize that the decision to maintain this population (organisms) as a ‘variety’ of the species 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bolanos, Quiroga &amp; Litvaitis" authorityYear="2007" box="[474,650,1036,1062]" class="Rhabditophora" family="Pseudoceritidae" genus="Pseudoceros" kingdom="Animalia" order="Polycladida" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="rawlinsonae">
<emphasis box="[474,650,1036,1062]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">P. rawlinsonae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the sole and exclusive responsibility of the authors. We are aware that ‘variety’ is not a taxonomic category (according to ICZN) and that therefore it will remain a non-existent species until molecular analyses allow us to consider it as such.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
